Regression Analysis¶

In [21]:
from scipy.stats import linregress
result = linregress(X, y)
print(result)

LinregressResult(slope=0.0005105948378163303, intercept=35.97336990669326, rvalue=0.8885991558970809, pvalue=0.0, stderr=5.133480974580817e-06, intercept_stderr=0.34807190031078566)
In [22]:
0.8885991558970809 ** 2 #r2
Out[22]:
0.7896084598610048

The estimated regression model is given by $$ y(x) = 0.0005105948378163303 x + 35.97336990669326 $$

where y = life expectancy x = income composition of resources

  • Thus, the portion of the life expectancy not explained by the income of individual is 35.97336990669326, i.e. if income = 0.
  • The average value of the life expectancy increases by approximately 0.0005105948378163303, on average, per hundred thousandths increase in income.
  • r = 0.8885991558970809 indicating a very strong positive linear relationship
  • The coefficient of determination r^2 is given by 0.78960845986100488. Thus, approximately 78.96% of the total variation of life expectancy is explained by the variation in income composition of resources.
  • p-value = 0 < 0.00 which is significant at 5% level of significance indicating that a linear relationship does exist between life expectancy and income composition of resources.

up = ((residual) ** 2) / ((sum(residual**2)) / len(residual))
